Here's how to handle all three requirements:

**1 & 2 — Intercept back navigation + confirm:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` in your page's code-behind:

```csharp
// EditProductPage.xaml.cs
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        // Fire-and-forget since override must return bool synchronously
        Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
            {
                _hasUnsavedChanges = false;
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            }
        });

        return true; // cancel the original navigation
    }
}
```

> **Note:** `OnBackButtonPressed` only fires for the **hardware/Android back button**. It does *not* fire when the user taps the Shell navigation bar's back arrow. That's where `BackButtonBehavior` comes in.

**3 — Custom "Cancel" back button (replaces the shell back arrow):**

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Title="Edit Product">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your view-model (or code-behind):

```csharp
// ViewModel or code-behind
public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

public EditProductViewModel()
{
    BackCommand = new Command(async () =>
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            return;
        }

        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (leave)
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    });
}
```

**Key takeaways:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` → handles **hardware** back (Android).
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` → handles the **shell toolbar** back arrow and lets you customize its text/icon.
- You need **both** to fully guard against accidental navigation.
